m kneel - by the bedside and mother as well. Yes. In them days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 They were practicing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12060953\charrsid3099254 C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 hristians, both of them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Oh yes, yes, oh yes, they were - good living - people as far as - ordinary people were concerned, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Did father have any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Well - well no, not a lot, I don't think that he - he - he attended many - meetings like you know - candidate meeting whatever might call them, I don't think so, I - he used to vote I think and mother used to vote.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 The women had the vote after 1918 didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Yes, yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Have you any idea what his views on politics would have been in the old days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Yes. Oh yes, I know, Liberal. Ackland was here, MP. F.D. Ackland I think he was called.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 He was the member for this constituency?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Oh yes, he - he ran here for years and years. I can mind he - running here I don't know but - before the first war I know that he was a - election on right after the first war, 1918, and he ran and - and - went in, he used 
to go in nearly every time because this was here Liberal - I mean division, here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 There were two elections in 1910. He would have voted Liberal each time I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Yes. Yes. Because there - there were only two parties here then. I - I - Liberal
s and - and Conservatives. Now I think - I don't know if it was 1910 one that might be the - one, that I can mind - a Conservative fellow ran here, by the name of - Norman Chamberlain, and he had a big car. It is either 1908 or 1910, I know it was be - fo
re the - first war, a good while. And he had a big car and he's - he was in the family with the Neville Chamberlain and all they, I think he was nephews to they. Nephew to 'em.
