\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Oh yes.
 Yes, that - yes, when I was a boy - well say about ten or twelve year old - I had a bike and used to - used to ride around a bit - I - I - of course I never had a very high bike because I was short. But still I - I had a bike and used to - ride around a 
bit, go Camborne on the bike or - just about - four or five mile like each way until I got older and then I used to do - I mean go to Hayle or somewhere like that there, seaside a bit. Venture out what they call.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 When you were a young man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Yes, yes, yes, adult age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 What about fishing, ever go fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well - up Chycarne Moor in the leat that's all, and if I get wet feet well I knew all about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 That's for tiddlers, not really fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 No, no. Minnows.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Go for walks sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Oh yes, Sundays we used to go out for - a walk after Sunday school. Down round by Killivose we used to go, and - Copper Hill, and - well, and go up Croft Common a bit and - you know and I have gone so far as Nine Maidens.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Would this be any special time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
No, no, no, no, if we - if - if two or three - boys or adults like when we was adults take in our head we used to say, we're going out for a walk. Well sometimes we used to go up Hangman Hill, or - and - as I said before, the other places.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 This would be with your pals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Oh yes, yes, yes, yes. And sometimes - it was - if it was a nice - evening and - dry, we would take - walk a bit, and a - another thing is I used to go institute a bit. Down here - have a game of cards and - a
nd billiards besides. I used to play billiards a bit - in them days of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Which institute would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Ah well - there was only one in Troon, I mean Village Institute. Before it - it became an institute, it - it was a - a Liberal - hall w
hat they call.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Liberal club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Club, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Did you take part in any sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Well - no, not actually but I used to go and - and watch you know cricket. Mind - our cricket team here, in Troon, is a lovely team because - they went through t
o - Lords you know, last year, and - yes, and they - yes. Now - when I came out Troon to live first - everybody out here was interested in cricket, even the - even the boys had bats - and balls in their hands, but the cricket team - as a - a - was a lovel
y team in them days. Kit Trevarthen - Vincent Grundy, Jo Niles, Stee Angove, well - I can't mention all of 'em but my God they was a good team in they days I'll tell you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Did you go to any theatres?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Yes. Well not theatres - theatres but in Cambor
ne, pictures, in - they used to call it Camborne - why - Scala in they days. It was called Scala.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Any concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Oh yes, we used to attend the concerts a bit because - nice to pass away the evenings concerts in the chapels or Sunday schools, don'
t matter which one it - which chapel or Sunday school it was, we didn't bother, about that so long as you've been to a concert, or Band of Hope concert or - well - well we used to go why - I used to go to most all the concerts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 That would be music mostly?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Any drama or poetry or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 No, I - I'm afraid I wasn't interested in they - in - in them very much, I was more interested in singing - than they things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Any music halls around here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 No, there's no music halls in Troon, only the chapels are giving concerts or - anything like that - like that you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 When you were a schoolboy did your parents give you any pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well - yes, yes. Well if I had a - a - a penny a week in they days. Pen
ny a week. You would look in the shop windows in Troon, and see what you could have for a ha'penny. And if you - you go in and have ha'porth of this and then you'd go - other end of Troon and have a look in the sweet shop and see what's there, and well - 
and then you go in - and have a - what do you call it, honeysuckle wheel in they days or - licorice strip or - or something like that. That was all we had in the week. Yes, and lucky to have that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 It was mostly spent on sweets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 On sweets, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Did anyone outside the home help your mother to look after her house and family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Well - I don't know what you exactly mean - do you mean if mother was - was ill or - or a bit poorly or something like that, oh yes, a neighbour used to come in then and used to give a - helping hand and mother would do the same for her if -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 You told me before about Mrs Eathorne?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Would that have been when you were at Porkellis or at Troon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Oh - at Porkellis, and Troon as well, now we lived - 
at Troon Moor, beside - beside a neighbour called - Williams, Mrs Williams, and - she was called - Mary and my mother's called Mary, and they would go to each other's doors if they never seen each other for - for a few hours like - say dinnertime and they
 
would - knock to the door and - and shout in, well - how are you Mary? Are you poorly, I haven't seen you for the morning. Oh no, well - yes, yes, I'm lying in for a couple of hours, I've got bit headache. Well that's all right, lie down for the day, I'll
 look after the children for ee, and your husband when he come home from work. Robert he was called. Yes, well - and mother would do the same for her. For her children too.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 That would be friends and neighbours, what about relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Neighbours. 
Well - well - we never had many at Troon you see, we had cousins out here. Yes, mother had a good - had one good neighbours, she was in the family a bit, she was a daughter to Kate - Williams, and - and Kate Williams was a cousin of my mother, first cousi
n, so - she was called - now wait a minute - I believe she - I believe she was called - Annie Jewell or something I think it was her name, I think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 This would be just in time of need?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Not regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Mother's - friends was really - at Porkellis, where she come from, she left her - her family or the - or}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14381211\charrsid3099254  what you call it, the cousins}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254  and all - all the family at Porkellis you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 If mother was ill or confined to bed how would she manage, do you remember what happened when your younger sister Rhoda was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Now I - there - there was a lady - an old lady - as far as I can mind that used to come - if - if women was going to have a child in they days, and look after the - the the child and the mother as well for a few days.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 How much would you see of relatives normally? Would they visit very often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Well mother's - you see - lived at - a good many mile away, five - mile - at Porkellis, but - they used to come out, my uncle - one of my uncles, Uncle Jack, he - he - 
he had a pony and trap, and my Uncle Henry had a - had a horse and trap and they used to come out - occasionally, not very often, but - occasionally to see mother, and - I know one at Porkellis - tea treat, we all walked up Porkellis from Troon, five mile
 
each way, and - and we walked - well, each way. And - we got home about - eleven or twelve o'clock that night, and left home about one o'clock after dinner. For tea treat at Porkellis and that was a - a big day up there, they used to have - arches over th
e gateway in the field, Porkellis, and they used to have the flags and banners out, my dear, it was some - and generally at Porkellis they had Falmouth band. Because - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Falmouth
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} from Porkellis was about - six or seven mile away, that was all. Now all right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Did the tea treats up there have the same kind of things as here, did they have the fair?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Well, only a - a small fair at the - I tell you what they used to have up there for the little kids - hand hobby horses what they call - turn 'em with a - turn the wheel with the hand - with their hands.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 And they would have the band?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 They'd - oh yes, they'd have a band. Oh yes, and - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 And }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14381211\charrsid3099254 sports}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 ?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Yes, yes. Sports for the children, and - well a bit - well few - you know, rings in t
he evening like they'd have anywhere else. Kidsing ring, Duggin ring, jolly miller and all that lot. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Did mother have any friends of her own apart from the family or relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 At Porkellis you mean? Or Troon. Yes, yes, yes. At Porkellis - or
 Troon, mother came out here - from Porkellis and - and made friends - right away because she was a - a sociable woman what they call, she could mix - a good mixer what they call my mother was, and the same thing where she come from up Porkellis.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 What about father, would he have any special friends of his own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Well - father was more - was more - what shall I say - reserved a bit he was my father was, but - he was all right - he was a - sociable - enough if you had a bit of chat with him or anythi
ng like that or wanted to chat with him he would speak to you and all like that there but he - he wasn't a good mixer really, he - he would - well he's more home in the evenings than - going out around like you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Where would mother see her friends normally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Oh yes, she used to - she used to go like I said over - over New Street, Mrs Williams, Mrs Hambley, Mrs Richards and - and the neighbours up around there where she lived and she used to go into the chapel, take interest in the chapel and -
 and father was a - he used to go class - a - a - meetings in they days what they call, and sang in the choir and - well took quite a - active part in the chapel, both did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Were friends invited into your home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Oh - my dear, somebody - Sundays or
 - or - any other time, there was anything doing, a concert out here or tea treat, well - we used to have them coming from - all - all around like, and - and they'd come out on bikes and - and leave their - all their bikes what they come on - out in the -
 in the back yard and they would go off concerts - with us and - tea treats and all and come back again - and go home on their bikes and - yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Would they be offered something to eat and drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Oh - oh yes, yes, yes - it don't matter who'd come 
in - our house, it should have been welcome home over the door - for - for - mother or father, 'cos they were - they make everybody welcome, and now come in, come in, now sit down. Now look, I'm going to make a cup of tea for ee.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Would you say that most of your friends were friends of you're your parents, father's and mother's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Did friends sometimes call in casually without invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well - if my mother and father was there in the garden or separate or - or - or - or together
 like chatting someone come on they would - stop and have a chat with them or - oh yes, and especially - I've got a good man in my mind and - I hold him in highest esteem, that was our old schoolmaster up here, Master Moorshead, he was a wonderful man and
 everybody - children or anyone else had - if they see - saw him on the street would always say - sir, morning, afternoon or evening, don't matter what time of the day it was, always sir. Looked up to him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 What about neighbours would they pop in casually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Oh yes. Neighbours yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
People often tell us that in those days they made their own amusements, what do you think you parents did, were there any special amusements when they got together with their friends? Or neighbours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well, it all
 depends - who they was, and who come here for - and - and the numbers. But - anybody could sing amongst them or - anything, well - down - why down round the organ we would go and have a good sing-song, but if there's one or two that wasn't interested ver
y much in singing and mother and - and father knew it, mother would say, well look - come out here in the kitchen a bit, well - I can't sing myself - we'll have a bit of chat together. So that's how it went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Would they ever play any games? No cards or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Oh yes, yes, I - when we was all home - of a winter evening and raining like a tide and - and - and the wind was hard and - well, you couldna shove out nowhere we used to have a game of - ludo or snakes and ladders if it's going o
r - or - you know, we used to amuse ourselves, yes, pass away the evening very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Many people did vide society into different social classes or groups, in that time before 1918 did you think of some people as belonging to one class and some to another?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Well, I suppose - it's like this, you mean this way I expect, that - there were some - I mean people that you - would look up to like because they were - well - as you call them today, they were so and so's, now you take - Squire Pendarves, wel
l he had a mansion and he had a - and he had a - gardens down a park and then he owned the hundreds of acres outside, farms and houses and all, but - we used to see him come up up Troon and - we used to - well ack - acknowledge him as - as a squire Pendar
v
es and and he used to - have his own men to do the work, hire men, he had a carpenter, he had a mason, he - he used to have masons, gardeners and - and - what was the other one he used to have - a gamekeeper. Two gamekeepers - Squire Pendarves had, becaus
e he had so much land and so much woods - and used to - rear - rabbits and - and pheasants in there, by the galore, and they used to - used to feed their pheasants - like anybody would keep ordinary chickens or - or fowls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Did he ever take any part in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Oh well - well Squire Pendarves gave them that cricket field and - and the recreation ground you know, and - Lady Pendarves of course, she was - looked up on as well as a lady because - I think that she was - she was something to the nur
sing, and the hospitals or something, and if she knew anybody was - taken sick or sick in the village I think that she would - come and visit them and - and I think she was - kind in other ways.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Can you recall anybody she visited like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well
 - well no, not I mean personally, I - she - she never did our - our family, but I've heard - people say - that she'd visit - people that was sick here Troon a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 In what ways have you heard she would have been kind to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Oh well - in them 
days there were - you - you know - big families and - if - if - if anyone was sick or the husband was sick or the father of the children was sick or anything and - well - I think that somebody would - pass it on to her and notify her that so and so - so a
n
d so was sick, I think that she would - come up in the - they used to have a - a landau what they call in they days with a horse or - horsedrawn and stop outside the - stop outside the doors I think and - went in to enquire - how's the sick and all like t
hat, well like anybody - should do - in her position, because - she was a lady, and we used to look on her as a Lady Pendarves, as the Lady Pendarves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Did they own any property in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Oh yes yes. Well - they used to own farms, and their 
- they're gone from the - of course - Mr Mendarves now and his wife - have passed on, a few years ago, but - before that - he used to own farms, and - he sold them afterwards, most of his farms are being sold to the farmers that was farming the land. And 
t
he houses - houses - yes, that rented the land, they bought their - had their own ground what they call from Mr Pendarves, and some houses - now - in Troon, years ago, and - elsewhere I - I suppose, that people used to build their houses years ago on a le
ase of ninety-nine years. But when that lease was up, ninety-nine years - they had to buy - the freehold of the land. Or the leasehold again, for another number of years.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 That's from the landowner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 From - from the landowner yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Can you think of any other person who you would have said was of a different class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Well now this old man - that I'm speaking about, he was a very old man, and he was - very saintly, we used to look upon him - in the village - as being a - a - a - saint what th
ey call. His name was - Mark Harris, old Mark Harris. And - and - he - used to - officiate over - over the - over the dead, he used to - that was his job over cemetery quite often - for - for - to officiate if anybody died, instead of a - a Minister or a 
-
 rector or - or parson or anything, he would do the job. He was licensed what they call for to carry out the burials. And - and when he prayed, he was always rubbing his hands together, you know, like that there he was, and - and - and we used to reckon -
 and - most people reckoned in Troon that he was a good old man, a saint.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 He would have been a preacher?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Oh a local preacher besides, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 What was his occupation, how did he earn his living?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well I - that I couldn't tell you, now when
 I come out Troon live - first - he was an old man then, yes, I suppose he was over eighty when he died, he must have been because - he must have.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 There was a Mr Harris who was a poet, would that be him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Now - Mr - Mr Mark Harris - a son to old 
John Harris - live up - the Chimneys what you call up there - Six - Chimney house, six Chimneys they call it, now he was a poet that moan was, old - John - Mark Har}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14381211\charrsid3099254 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 is was the son to him and then he had a son a local preacher, called Jacob Harris. And - he'd got a son near Troon now called Leslie}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14381211\charrsid3099254  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Harris, and he - he's over seventy, and he's a big chapel man - well - looks to me it's handed down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 You would have classed Mr Harris as rather a higher class than most in the village?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Oh - oh - oh yes,
 for being - I don't say that he's any - any better christian than others, you know what I mean - but that people used to look upon him I suppose as his age - and did it so long and - and connected with the - funerals and all I suppose and that was - that
's how it was, but I used to think he was - a saintly man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Within the village itself would you have felt that there was any classification of society, was there any classes within the actual village, any that would consider themselves as a higher or a lower class, or that you would consider so?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Well, I suppose at Troon - you can reckon there's a working class like village and - I don't think that they would - they would try to - be one up on the other, I don't think so, the shopkeepers and the - a
nd the ordinary village people was - much on the same level I think, I don't think that anybody was trying to ride each other what they call. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Would you say you belonged to the same class as most of the people in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well, I reckon m
yself - I aren't boasting mind, but I reckon myself that I'm - equal and they're equal to me. The working class - yes, yes, yes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well - w
hen I was a lad coming up - I used to talk to - respect my elders. Not go out Troon as a lad - and a - a man sixty or seventy come along and call him by his christian name, I - I was ex - expected - from my mother and father - to call him mister or - or -
 or a woman missus, if they were married, or if they wasn't married you would look - call them by their christian names.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Were you ever told to touch your cap to anyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well - yes, I - I - I have touched me cap to anyone, and especially a funeral
 coming on, if I saw a funeral, the hearse coming or - or a coffin - being carried - I - I would pause on the sidewalk until the coffin - whether it's carried by hand or in the hearse, and take me cap off. Out of respect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Can you think of any other wa
ys you showed respect, you were saying about the schoolmaster and Mr Harris, can you think of any other people in the village as a lad or later you would have thought were to be held in higher regard? Was there any-one you called sir or master or madam?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Well - no, I don't think that I - I - I should really but there were other men there that - that - I respected all the same, but - you know Mr Berriman - why Jimmy Berriman - you know butcher that used to be, he used to keep greyhound dogs and he used 
to show them, and - he sent dogs even to America.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 As an authority?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
For - well he used to sell them, he used to breed the greyhounds, and show them. He didn't keep them for - racing, he keep them - kept them for showing, and - he sent - he sent them to - America, he was well known - for - for greyhound dogs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 He was a butcher?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
He - yes, yes, he was the butcher. And - and Mr Bastion, the shoemaker, kept the shoemakers shop here Fore Street, we used to look up to him. Of course - what - o
f course he used to won this house when we come out here to live first, he was - he was our landlord in them days, Mr Bastion was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 And he was the shoemaker?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well, and a shop besides and - yes, yes, that's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Did you come into contact with them very much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well - yes. When I was a lad, he used to do - he used to mend for a shop in Camborn, Lennard}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14381211\charrsid3099254 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 s shop, the boot shop, and he used to do the - what was - they used to send - up the boots and - and shoes to be mended and Mr Bastio
n - and then - he would - ask me for take 'em down to the shop in Camborne. After he - he - he repaired the - boots and shoes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 This is when you were a schoolboy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Oh when I was a schoolboy, yes, yes, yes, yes, yes, that's right, after school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Did he pay you for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Oh yes, yes, well a trifle like - you know, well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Why would you think these folk were considered important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well - I suppose that - being - being shopkeepers I suppose we used to look up to them a bit becau
se they - they - kept the shop and - Mr - and Mrs Pendarves like was - they were - lords of the land what they call in they days, the squires and - old Mr Harris - looked upon him as a saint and - well, and that was how things went in them days. And a - a
nother - man I used to like when I was at the school was called Mr Arthur Harvey, he was the teacher. I used to like Mr Arthur Harvey.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Shopkeepers, who would they associate with as friends, sort of visiting friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well I don't think the shopkee
pers had much time in them days 'cos they used to open early and shut late. Yes. Excuse me. In Camborne when I was - when I was a lad I used to go down there - Christmas Even, when I got up - on a bit, a lad what you might call - we used to sing - carols 
-
 in Commercial Square after the shops were shut and they never shut before - eleven o'clock back in they days, and we used to sing and leave Camborne about twelve and arrive at Troon about half past twelve or quarter to one, and singing all the way home t
hen from Camborne.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 What about the clergy, who would they consider themselves equal with or mix with as friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well the - well the ministers was - we had very good ministers here I think in the both chapels. But - the first one that - that I ca
n mind, really mind, was called - Dewarton, the Reverend - Hartley Dewarton, I think it - Hartley Dewarton I think he was, and - United Methodist minister and - he had a - a male voice choir, he was the conductor or a male voice choir in them days, and - 
they used to go round and - to the different chapels and give concerts, and they were a very nice choir.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Where would the choir have been, where would he have had his choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Oh - oh in Camborne, yes, yes, yes, Camborne, it was a male voice choir.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Did any of the Troon people belong in this choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Well, yes, I can mind one man from Troon, he - passed on now, Mr Roberts, from - from Troon. And Bertie Roberts he was called. He was in it for - for years all I know of and he - of course the Re
verend Dewarton was here for - a good time, I don't know if he ever - had his - his ministry extended a bit, 'cos he was a very popular man, he was - he was in they days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Did the clergy mix socially with the people, like go to their houses to tea or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Well - they'd never - I don't think that they've been ever here to tea, but they - they'd knock on the door and - and inquired and all you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Come for a chat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Yes, come for a bit of a chat like, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 What about teachers, who would they mix with socially or consider their friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well do you mean teachers in the Sunday school or in the everyday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 The teachers mostly in the everyday schools.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well - well - well no, if we was - well no, th
ey used to - mix with the chaps, if they was in the sport - sports or anything they would come or if there's any cricketers amongst them they would - join the cricket and - oh no, I don't think there was any - anybody aloof what they call it, they was all
 friendly. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 What about farmers, were they any different class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Well I - I think that - I think the farmers here on the whole was - was very good, mother used to - have her milk from - when we was over Troon Moor, up Dick Adams and we had to 
fetch it in a jug in the morning and evenings, and when we came up - up the other side of Troon, where we are now, Chapel Square, we used to - used to buy it of Mr - Mr Hampton and he used to have a - have a - have a - what do you call it in them days - w
ith the measures hanging down, you could have a half pint or pint or whatever you like. And we used to have our cream in - in Mrs Hampton's.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 They all mixed the same as the working people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Oh yes, yes, yes, yes. All mixed together very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 What about employers, can you think of who were the employers in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Well - well when I was in the mine working and - and - I was asked to do anything or - what I supposed to do I done and - and that was that, I was in the tin yard and I work
ed under Mr Shearman - for a while, for quite a while, and then I went out on other jobs on top in the mine and - I got on all right - all right, we used to call 'em captains in they day, we got on all right with the captains, they was - if we done our wo
rk that was all was needed of us, and they - and that was all they - troubled about us, or - or bothered about us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Would you see anything of them in the village or know who they'd mix with socially?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well - the captains in the mines in they days w
as - there were underground bosses and - well - well on floor I mean bosses, what they call on top bosses what they call, well they used to go to the chapels and they would - mix with the men and - well like every - like everyone else in the chapel, if th
ey was in the choir they was in the choir with the others, and if they was - in the chapel, well - they would sit with other people. There wouldn't be a distance what they call, not distant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 What sort of people would you say went to the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 C
hurch of England? Well - about the same, we - we - we're all - all in the village, same I mean village, it wasn't any difference, not - so - some of the neighbours went and - oh well some were chapel people and others were church people, but - I didn't se
e any difference, not in - in their attitude or their manners at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Where did }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14381211\charrsid3099254 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
he Pendarves' go?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Church people. Oh yes, they were church they were. Yes. And they had a son - called - Stackhouse Pendarves, John Stackhouse Pendarves, well he was a - he was a sidesman down church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Treslothan church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Yes. Yes, yes, yes. Well I used to go - I used to go myself - quite often down church, I - I have - I sung in the choir down there for a while. Mm. I got the photo upstairs now, cassock and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14381211\charrsid3099254 
surplice}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Most of the village people went to the chapels?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Well - you can say that - well in the - when I come out here first, the - the church was - the church was very well - attended. But - like the church and the chapels are here now and - it
 looks to me it's a trend through the country, they're getting a bit thinner. People in going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Where you lived here in Troon and before did all the people in the - your own group, working class as we call, have the same standard of living, or would yo
u say that within our own working class groups there were some who were different, some had a better standard of living than others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well - I couldn't say that because we - we're - we're all working class together, rather we were in the mines working
, or - some people used to work down Holman's Foundry in Camborne. Well - we was all the same, we all mixed together and I don't - I don't know they had anything - more in life than - than what we had that work in the mines, we were all sociable and - and
 the - men and women - either their sons were a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14381211\charrsid3099254 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254  Holman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14381211\charrsid3099254 /}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 s or in the mines, they were all the same, when they meet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Do you remember any distinction between craftsmen such as carpenters or fitter and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well, the carpenters and fitters and 
masons, what you might call the tradesmen - had a - a bit higher pay than a - than a general labourer would have, well that's natural because they had to serve their time, and when they were serving their time years ago, it weren't more than about a shill
ing or eighteen pence a week you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Were some families thought of as rough and others as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Well, I don't - know of anybody in Troon - was had up for anything very - serious and I don't think that any - anybody had do a long term of - of imprisonment, I don't think so, I think that they were - well, on the whole law abiding. Very good for that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class or group?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 No, I - I do not, I think my mother - was
 a - good mix and would mix with anyone or - or - she was very sociable and - I don't think she used to think herself above any - anybody else at all. She was on the same level and she would h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14381211\charrsid3099254 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 pe that they would be with her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Did mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Yes. There was no difference.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well as - as I said before, why Lady Pendarves and - and Squire Pendarves, of cours
e they owned - they were the - lords of - of the land that they owned that time, they had a great mansion and - and parks and - gamekeeper and gardener and carpenters and all these things I said, well - you would - of course I mean they were employers, in
 that day, on their estate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Would you think that would be why they would be classed as real gentlemen, becau}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14381211\charrsid3099254 se of their property and owning}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well - well, no. I - I wouldn't consider that not as a wholly - for that, I think that they were nice a -
 people, because I think they - I think they did some good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Do you remember seeing a policeman around as a child? What did you think of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well - boys in they days didn't like to see a policeman. Even if we didn't do anything - anything wrong,
 we used to stand in fear of 'em a bit. Nowaday}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14381211\charrsid3099254 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254  well - if the Panda cars and you can see 'em coming, but in them days we -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 When you were naughty, if you ever were, did your mother ever say I'll call a policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 No, I - I - I never heard her sa
y that, but I - but - I can mind - the first one policeman when I come out Troon to live first, he wasn't - wasn't stationed near Troon then, in Beacon. His name was Kingdon, PC Kingdon when I come here first in Troon. That was 1905. And he was a great ta
ll thin fellow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 How do you think he treated the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
Well - I suppose - if you do anything wrong or - or what you shouldn't ought to do I suppose and they - saw you do it and - well of course they would - chat to ee or tell ee - or warn ee you
 mustn't do it again, but the second time why - I've heard - now I've never had it done myself but I've heard - if a - a lad or anything done anything a bit wrong, bobby would come on and - and give ee a little bit of - a bit of touch behind the ear like 
a
nd go on, nowadays this - well - we did stand - we did stand in fear - of a policeman, in them days, until we got - up in our teens what they call and then of course we come to realize then what they was for and - they had to keep the - had to keep the la
w and the peace and the - that was the end of that so if we transgress - we should know all about it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 You told me that your home was rented, did you see anything of your landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Oh yes, yes, used to come - Mr - yes, Mr Bastion used to come up 
here - quite often, and - and - and - and we used to take - rent to him, down to him once a month.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 What did you feel about him as a landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well - I suppose we can say - reasonable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Did he keep the place in good repair?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well if ther
e's - if there's anything wanted to be done we used to go to Mr Bastion and say, well look Mr Bastion, why - of course this is outside the house, now the interior is supposed to be us isn't it, painting and - and - and papering and that, unless - it was a
 
big job inside that - that would come under the landlord, we used to do - all the inside ourselves and - and a lot - a bit more sometimes than we should have done, but then we done that for - because the - rent was a bit cheap in them days and - we didn't
 mind, but Mr Bastion - on the whole - wasn't too bad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6423890 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Do you remember feeling that your parents had to struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12409093 WF  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 Well, they never had anything for to - for to throw away, I mean to say it was - the pay was small in them days, b
ut things were cheap. You could go in Camborne - of a Saturday - evening - and mother used to go, and father, used to go - Camborne of a Saturday evening and go in the market house and come away about - just before - closing time, they used to go in and -
 
and they could have a tag of beef - in they days for half crown. That's for two days, Sunday and Monday. Be - yes - yes, yes, it had to be - nearly closing down time. And then - of course they couldn't save the - in them days because they never had nothin
g for put them in, no - no fridge, or nothing like that, so - and at the Summertime especially - if they put it anywhere - the - the flies would get after it and it wouldn't - it wouldn't be no good to se}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14381211\charrsid3099254 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 l the Monday. So - that was how - it - it went off a
 bit cheap. And another thing is - we lads - in Troon - we would go in Camborne of a Saturday evening, first thing was - Moncini's - fish and chips. Now that was four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14381211\charrsid3099254  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 pence. In - in pictures five}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14381211\charrsid3099254  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254 
pence. We would come out from there and go in the market hou
se to have a basin of booth - for a penny. And the lady who kept that on was - was called Roskilly. Mind I'm going back now mind when I was - well - oh, yes, yes, well early teenage at that. And then from there - we used to go up to - a shop called - we u
s
ed to call it Father East, and he used to sell - jelly and blancmange. Now all that - would come in the shilling. That was Saturday. Yes, and blancmange yes. Now that would all come in - in the shilling. Pictures, chips, jelly and blancmange, basin of bro
th, now if you're going to have it nowaday}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14381211\charrsid3099254 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10693638\charrsid3099254  it'd cost you a quid, easy.
